strength and direction of consistently increasing or decreasing relationships"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ESpearman rank correlation coefficient measures strength and direction of consistently increasing or decreasing relationships\u003C/strong\u003E between variables. It is particularly useful for ordinal data or when the relationship between variables is not linear but follows a consistent trend in one direction.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasures only linear relationships between variables\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike Pearson correlation, Spearman correlation can detect any consistently trending relationship, not just linear ones\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires normally distributed data\u003C/strong\u003E - As a non-parametric test, Spearman correlation does not require normal distribution\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECan only be used with continuous variables\u003C/strong\u003E - Spearman correlation works with ordinal data and ranked variables\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlways produces positive values between 0 and 1\u003C/strong\u003E - Spearman correlation coefficients range from -1 to +1\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe coefficient ranges from -1 (perfect negative correlation) through 0 (no correlation) to +1 (perfect positive correlation). The rank transformation makes it resistant to outliers and suitable for non-normal distributions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spearman rank correlation measures the strength and direction of consistently increasing or decreasing relationships between ordinal or ranked variables.","Spearman correlation coefficients range from -1 to +1, where -1 indicates perfect negative correlation and +1 indicates perfect positive correlation.","Spearman correlation is non-parametric and does not require normally distributed data or linear relationships."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55692"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17380"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55692"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T09:44:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T09:46:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10070"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70228"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"